(Mutant for Hire) wrote:

> Just a point here but Intel is having migranes trying to keep
> increasing the speed of the x86 line of processors while keeping
> binary compatibility. I'm sure there are plenty of Intel people
> who would love just scrapping the instruction set and starting
> over, but since there's the installed base, they're stuck with
> it for a good time.

I agree.  Backwards compatibility is about the only thing these two have
to hold them up.  Innovation is suppressed because of the baggage the
architecture had to carry, since the 8080 days.  Plus, Intel doesn't have
any high powered chip that will compete with the PowerPCs at this moment. 
Sure they talk about the next generation x86, but it will have the same
problems the Pentium had upon introduction.  High cost, high power
consumption, low register count.  There is only so much you can build
upon, then you have to scrap everything and start anew.

